 in late-stage clinical development. Their availability offers opportunity for increased patient access across a number of oncologic indications. The regulatory pathway for biosimilar approval relies on the totality of evidence that includes a comprehensive analytical assessment, and a clinical comparability study in a relevant disease patient population. Extrapolation of indications for a biosimilar to other eligible indications held by the originator, in the absence of direct clinical comparison, frequently forms part of the regulatory judgment. Herein, we consider the evidence required to demonstrate biosimilarity for bevacizumab biosimilars, with particular focus on the rationale for extrapolation across oncologic indications.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Melosky</LastName><ForeName>Barbara</ForeName><Initials>B</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Medical Oncology, British Columbia Cancer Agency, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC V5Z 4E6, Canada.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Reardon</LastName><ForeName>David A</ForeName><Initials>DA</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Center for Neuro-Oncology, Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, Boston, MA 02215, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Nixon</LastName><ForeName>Andrew B</ForeName><Initials>AB</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medicine/Medical Oncology, Duke University School of Medicine, Durham, NC 27710, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Subramanian</LastName><ForeName>Janakiraman</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Oncology, Saint Luke's Cancer Institute, Kansas City, MO 64111, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Bair</LastName><ForeName>Angel H</ForeName><Initials>AH</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Pfizer Inc., New York, NY 